ntracts.\n*   **Connectivity Segment:** Revenue is primarily from Starlink consumer/enterprise broadband and equipment sales.\n*   **AI Segment:** Revenue includes subscriptions and services from the **X platform and Grok**.\n\n**3. How xAI / X Platform Revenue Flows:**\nThe text explicitly integrates X and Grok into the **AI segment**.\n*   The **AI segment** "operates a vertically integrated AI platform spanning a frontier LLM Grok, AI solutions for consumer and enterprise customers, **X — a real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform**."\n*   Financial results for the AI segment directly include X and Grok performance. For example, the quarter-over-quarter revenue increase for the AI segment was attributed to **"higher X and Grok subscriptions."**\n*   Therefore, revenue from the **X platform and Grok AI services** is consolidated under the **AI segment** within SpaceX\'s financial statements.\n\n**4. Segment Performance Measurement (CODM):**\nThe Chief Operating Decision Maker (CODM) evaluates segment performance based on **income (loss) from operations**, comparing it to historical and forecasted results. This operating income figure is then reconciled to **Segment Adjusted EBITDA** by adding back depreciation, amortization, share-based compensation, and certain charges like restructuring and impairment.\n\n### Summary of Inter-Segment Transaction Logic\nThe primary intercompany flow described is a **strategic subsidy from Space to Connectivity (and future AI) via launch capacity**:\n*   **Space Segment:** Provides launches at cost (no inter-segment revenue). Its reported revenue is understated relative to its operational utilization.\n*   **Connectivity/AI Segments:** Receive launch services at cost, which is capitalized as a long-lived asset (satellites, compute hardware). The expense is then recognized via depreciation over the asset\'s useful life.\n*   **Consolidated Effect:** The cost of the launch appears in the **Connectivity/AI segme