ials reflect the "retrospective combination of the entities" and that "all historical related party transactions between the entities have been eliminated in consolidation." This suggests the data arrangement is treated as an intra-company operational synergy rather than an external licensing contract.\n\n### 3. Relationship Between Starlink and xAI Compute Infrastructure\nThe prospectus outlines a vision where Starlink\'s satellite constellation and connectivity would provide the backbone for xAI\'s future orbital compute infrastructure.\n\n*   **Starlink as the Connectivity Layer for Orbital AI:** The strategic vision is to deploy "AI compute satellite constellations—with potentially millions of satellites—for orbital data centers." These satellites in Sun-synchronous orbit would handle energy-intensive AI workloads (like inference) at scale. **Starlink would provide the "low-latency, global connectivity" linking these orbital AI systems to users worldwide, delivering "real-time intelligence."**\n*   **Synergistic Deployment:** SpaceX believes its reusable rockets (like Starship), scaled satellite manufacturing, and operational expertise (demonstrated with Starlink) can enable the "cost-effective and rapid deployment" of these massive AI compute satellite constellations.\n*   **Technical Foundation:** SpaceX claims to have "already solved many of the significant technical hurdles to evolving connectivity satellites into AI compute satellites" by leveraging Starlink\'s existing capabilities, including constellation-scale management, autonomous operations, over-the-air updates, and inter-satellite laser communications.\n\n### 4. Pre-Merger Provision of Services by SpaceX to xAI\nThe provided excerpts **do not contain any explicit mention of SpaceX providing launch services, Starlink connectivity, or satellite manufacturing for xAI satellite deployments or orbital data centers prior to the mergers.**\n\n*   The narrative focuses on the future potential unlocked by the combination. The "unmatched satellite launch capabilities" of SpaceX are cited as the "foundational competitive advantage" that enables the future vision for orbital AI data centers.\n*   The mergers (xAI acquiring X in March 2025, and SpaceX acquiring xAI in February 2026) are accounted for as transactions between entities under **common control** due to Elon Musk\'s majority voting interest in each. This accounting treatment (retrospective combination) implies that any inter-company services would have been eliminated or treated as internal capital movements in the consolidated financial statements presented, rather than as external service contracts.\n\n**In summary:** The prospectus presents Grok\'s integration with X as a key data-driven advantage for the AI model. Starlink is positioned as the future global connectivity network for SpaceX\'s planned orbital AI compute infrastructure. While specific data licensing or pre-merger service contracts are not detailed, the document emphasizes the strategic synergies and vertical integration enabled by bringing these entities under common control.',
