atement:\n\n> "We allocate a significant amount of launch capacity to our Connectivity segment, and **expect to allocate a significant amount to our AI segment in the future**."\n\nThis suggests that future launches for the AI segment (presumably deploying AI compute infrastructure or data centers to space) will follow the **same treatment** — no inter-segment revenue recognition in the Space segment, with costs capitalized in the benefiting segment.\n\n### CODM Does Not Use Consolidated GAAP Measures for Segment Evaluation\n\n> "The Company\'s CODM assesses performance and allocates resources to operating segments based on **segment income (loss) from operations** by comparing actual income (loss) from operations to historical results and previously forecasted financial information. The Company\'s CODM **does not evaluate operating and reportable segments using** [GAAP net income — sentence appears truncated]."\n\nThis suggests the CODM reviews segment-level P&Ls that have already had intersegment transactions eliminated or netted, meaning the segment tables presented (e.g., 2023, 2024, Q1 2025, and 2025 data) reflect the **post-elimination** view.\n\n---\n\n## What\'s NOT Disclosed in These Chunks\n\nBased on a thorough review of all provided text, the following items are **not present** in the excerpts:\n\n| Topic | Status |\n|---|---|\n| **Explicit transfer pricing methodology** (e.g., market-based, cost-plus, or negotiated pricing) | ❌ Not found in these chunks |\n| **Quantified intersegment revenue elimination amounts** | ❌ Not found — no separate line for intersegment eliminations appears in the segment tables |\n| **AI segment receiving services from Space or Connectivity segments** (e.g., shared compute, data center hosting, or satellite bandwidth for AI operations) | ❌ Not explicitly disclosed beyond the future launch capacity allocation |\n| **Pre-merger xAI and X intercompany flows** (e.g., whether xAI paid X for data, compute, or licensing; how the X platform and xAI\'s Grok model were transacting before the February 2026 acquisition) | ❌ Not found in these chunks |\n| **Post-merger intercompany flows between AI segment entities** (xAI, X, and other acquired entities) | ❌ Not found |\n| **Whether the AI segment\'s cost of revenue includes charges from the Connectivity segment** (e.g., Starlink bandwidth for AI inference or data transfer) | ❌ Not found |\n| **Whether share-based compensation or other corporate overhead is allocated across segments** | ❌ Not explicitly detailed beyond the supplemental tables showing SBC by segment |\n\n---\n\n## Analytical Observations\n\n1. **The intersegment launch treatment creates a structural distortion** in segment profitability. The Space segment\'s reported revenue ($4,086M for Q1 2026) and operating loss ($(657M)) **understate its true economic contribution** because the massive value it provides by launching Starlink satellites is captured only as capitalized assets in the Connectivity segment. The company itself acknowledges this:\n\n   > "As a result, notwithstanding an increasing launch cadence, our Space segment has **relatively lower revenue scale and revenue growth** compared to our other segments, though its financial results **do not reflect the foundational strategic value** that it provides to us in bolstering the growth of our Connectivity and AI segments."\n\n2. **The segment tables appear to show consolidated totals without a visible intersegment elimination line**, which implies that either:\n   - All intersegment transactions are eliminated before the segment-level line items are presented, or\n   - The only significant intersegment transaction (Space → Connectivity launches) is handled through capitalization rather than revenue/cost recognition, so there\'s nothing to eliminate in the P&L.\n\n3. **The AI segment\'s heavy R&D costs** ($3,888M increase in 2025 driven by GPU depreciation and cloud computing) raise the question of whether any of this compute in