All historical financial statements are presented *as if* xAI and X had always been part of SpaceX, with net assets carried at their **historical carrying amounts**\n- **No new goodwill or intangible assets** recorded in the Mergers\n- **All historical related-party transactions** between the entities were **eliminated in consolidation**\n- This means xAI\'s costs were *not* separately allocated pre-merger in the presentation — they were retroactively folded into the AI segment for all periods shown\n\nThe timeline:\n- **October 2022**: Musk acquired Twitter (renamed X)\n- **March 2023**: X.AI Corp began operations\n- **March 28, 2025**: X Merger — xAI acquired X Holdings Corp and X.AI Corp\n- **February 2, 2026**: xAI Merger — SpaceX acquired xAI\n\n---\n\n## AI Segment Cost Structure\n\n### Cost of Revenue Components\n| Category | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **Infrastructure costs** | Data center facilities (lease/hosting), support, maintenance, energy, bandwidth |\n| **Server/network depreciation** | Depreciation of servers and networking equipment |\n| **Public cloud hosting** | Cloud computing costs for operations |\n| **Employee compensation** | Salaries, benefits, share-based compensation |\n| **Revenue share** | Payments to content creators |\n| **Payment processor fees** | Transaction processing costs |\n| **Acquired intangible amortization** | Amortization from acquisitions |\n\n**Management expectation**: AI cost of revenue to *increase in absolute dollars* as revenue grows, but to *decrease as a percentage of revenue* as products are monetized.\n\n### R&D Expense Components\n| Category | Description |\n|---|---|\n| **Grok model training** | Training of the "leading frontier model" |\n| **Product development** | Next-gen AI-enabled products |\n| **Data center costs** | Costs to train AI-enabled products |\n| **Cloud computing** | Cloud expenses for R&D workloads |\n| **GPU hardware depreciation** | The **single largest driver** of R&D increase (~$1,471M in Q1 2026 alone) |\n| **Power generation costs** | Energy for compute infrastructure |\n| **Employee compensation** | Salaries, benefits, SBC |\n\n**Management expectation**: AI R&D to increase **both in absolute dollars and as a percentage of revenue** as compute infrastructure investment scales.\n\n### SG&A Components\n- Sales, marketing, finance, legal, IT, HR, and admin employee compensation\n- Professional services (consulting, content moderation, legal, accounting)\n- Facilities costs and supporting overhead\n- **Management expectation**: Increase in absolute dollars, decrease as % of revenue over time\n\n### Restructuring Charges\nAI restructuring charges trace back to the **Twitter acquisition in October 2022** and include:\n- Cash severance expense\n- Other termination benefits from ongoing global workforce reductions (effects continued into 2026)\n\n---\n\n## X Platform Integration into AI Segment\n\nThe filing is clear that **X is fully integrated into the AI segment**:\n\n> "In 2023 and 2024, substantially all of our AI segment revenue consisted of advertising, subscriptions, and data licensing revenue generated from X, formerly known as Twitter."\n\nThe AI segment is described as encompassing:\n- **Grok** (frontier LLM)\n- **AI solutions** for consumer and enterprise customers\n- **X platform** (real-time information, entertainment, and free speech platform)\n- **AI computational infrastructure**\n\nRevenue streams within the AI segment:\n1. **Advertising** on X (recognized when engagement occurs; seasonal — highest in Q4, lowest in Q1)\n2. **X and Grok subscriptions** (recognized ratably, month-to-month to 1-year terms)\n3. **Data licensing** (recognized ratably, month-to-month to 2-year terms)\n4. **API access to Grok** (recognized ratably or on usage basis, month-to-month to 1-year terms)\n\n---\n\n## Key Structural Observations\n\n1. **The AI segment\'s operating loss trajectory is stark**: From $(3,973)M in 2023 to $(1,561)M in 2024 (improving), then **ballooning to $(6,355)M in 2025** as compute investment accelerated, with quarterly losses deepening from $(936)M to $(2,469)M in Q1 2026.\n\n2. **R&D is exploding**: From $186M in 2023 → $1,176M in 2024 → ~$5,064M in 2025, driven almost entirely by GPU depreciation and cloud computing — the scaling laws investment.\n\n3. **Capital expenditure surge**: AI CapEx went from $463M (2023) → $5,633M (2024), representing a massive infrastructure buildout. Q1 2025 alone was $2,567M.\n\n4. **Nameplate compute draw**: Grew from 0 GW (2023) → 0.3 GW (2024) → 0.8 GW (2025) → 1.0 GW (Q1 2026), quantifying the physical infrastructure scale.\n\n5. **Multi-year horizon**: Management repeatedly warns it expects "a multi-year investment horizon before these deployments translate into sustained positive AI Segment Adjusted EBITDA."',
